  <p>When the FIFA World Cup kicks off on June 11, 2026, it will trigger the largest concentrated sports-betting event the Philippines' licensed online sportsbooks have faced since the regulatory shock of August 2025. For six weeks, an expanded 48-team tournament will deliver 104 matches — nearly twice the group-stage volume of any previous World Cup — across a window that overlaps almost every day with peak Philippine evening hours.</p>

  <p>For the PAGCOR-licensed PIGO sportsbook sector, the timing is consequential. The tournament arrives roughly four months after PAGCOR cut the live sports betting gross gaming revenue (GGR) share rate from 17.5 percent to 15 percent, and against the backdrop of a licensed online market still absorbing the structural impact of the August 2025 e-wallet delinking order.</p>

